caption:
Table 1: 
The overall assessment of quantized DeepSeek-R1-Distill-Qwen models on various reasoning benchmarks. QuaRot for the 7B model weight-activation quantization is skipped because of the incompatible hidden dimension for Hadamard transformation.
The green, orange and red cells stand for the lossless (≤\leq≤1%), the fair (1%-3%) and the risky (≥\geq≥3%) respectively.
Note that 1.5B and 7B models are exceptions with severe degradation for low-bit KV cache and weight-activation quantization, as will be discussed in Appendix C.2.
Results on more models are available in Appendix B.
description: This table presents a comprehensive evaluation of various quantization techniques applied to the DeepSeek-R1-Distilled Qwen family of reasoning language models.  It assesses performance across five diverse reasoning benchmarks (AIME-120, MATH-500, GSM8K, GPQA-Diamond, LiveCodeBench) for different model sizes (1.5B, 7B, 14B, 32B parameters).  Quantization methods evaluated include weight-only, KV cache, and weight-activation quantization using varying bit widths.  The results highlight the impact of different quantization approaches, model sizes, and task difficulty on overall accuracy.  Performance is categorized as lossless (≤1% accuracy drop), fair (1-3% drop), or risky (≥3% drop).  Specific findings regarding the 1.5B and 7B models with lower bit-width KV cache and weight-activation quantization are noted, with a reference to further discussion in Appendix C.2.  Additional results for other models are provided in Appendix B.

description: This table presents a comprehensive evaluation of the QwQ-32B large language model (LLM) under various quantization techniques.  It assesses the model's performance across five distinct reasoning benchmarks: AIME-120, MATH-500, GSM8K, GPQA-Diamond, and LiveCodeBench.  Each benchmark tests different aspects of reasoning ability, ranging from mathematical problem-solving to code generation. The table shows the performance impact of different quantization methods (weight-only, KV cache, and weight-activation) with varying bit-widths (3, 4, 8, 16 bits), using state-of-the-art quantization algorithms.  The performance drop is categorized into three levels: lossless (≤1% accuracy drop), fair (1%-3% accuracy drop), and risky (≥3% accuracy drop) to easily identify acceptable versus risky quantization strategies.  This allows for a clear comparison of different approaches and provides insights into the trade-off between accuracy and computational efficiency when quantizing LLMs for reasoning tasks.

description: This table presents the results of an experiment evaluating the impact of a pre-bias quantization technique on the DeepSeek-R1-Distill-Qwen language models, specifically the 1.5B and 7B parameter versions. Pre-bias quantization is a method used to improve the performance of quantized models, particularly in the context of KV cache (key-value cache) quantization. The table shows the performance of these models across various reasoning benchmarks (AIME-120, MATH-500, GSM8K, GPQA-Diamond, and LiveCodeBench) using different quantization configurations.  The performance is evaluated based on accuracy and the impact (drop in accuracy) compared to the baseline (BF16).  The color-coding of the cells aids in interpreting the results: green indicates near-lossless quantization (accuracy drop ≤1%), orange indicates fair performance (accuracy drop between 1% and 3%), and red indicates risky quantization (accuracy drop ≥3%). This allows readers to quickly assess the effectiveness of the pre-bias method at various bit-widths for different models and tasks.
